VM Specification

64 bit variables / registers
128 registers, identified by a single byte
top bit in the register opcode tells if it is treated as a value or a reference

a set of result flags:
zero
positive
negative
error


each instruction is 32 bit wide.
some instructions are followed by one or two data fields.
if one field this is used as a 32 bit constant
if two fields the seconds field are the high bits)

the instruction is split into four parts:
opcode (top 8 bits:  the actual instruction opcode
mods  (bits 16-23):  modifiers to instruction
target (bits 8-15):  the destination register
data (bits 0-7) the source or data register

mods are:
const 7,6:  0 - no constant
            1 - use 32 bit constant
            2 - use 64 bit constant
            3 - not used
condition   0 - no condition
            1 - execute if zero
            2 - execute if positive
            3 - execute if negative
            4 - execute if error

opcodes are:
load        load the value from data into target
load32      load a 32 bit constant into target
load64      load a 64 bit constant into target
ahead       use the value of the target and data together as a 16 bit offset to be added to the PC
back        use the value of the target and data together as a 16 bit offset to be subtracted from the PC
jump        jump to the value in target data is ignored
jump32      jump to a 32 bit address, registers are ignored
jump64      jump to a 64 bit address registers are ignored


branch      conditional jump to target based on the value in data
            if const flag is used the value from the following instructions fields are loaded instead and target is ignored
            error flag is set if target is outside of available space
call        jump to the value in target the pc is stored into data
            if const flag is used the value from the following instructions fields are loaded instead
            error flag is set if target is outside of available space
add         add the value
subtract
multiply
divide
compare
halt        terminate the running program
